[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] In computer programming, **create, read, update, and delete** (**CRUD**) are the four basic operations (actions) of persistent storage.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] CRUD is also sometimes used to describe user interface conventions that facilitate viewing, searching, and changing information using computer-based forms and reports.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] The term *CRUD* was likely first popularized in 1983 by James Martin in his book *Managing the data-base environment*.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] Data can be put in a *location/area* of a storage mechanism.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] Together these four operations make up the basic operations of storage management known as CRUD: *Create*, *Read*, *Update* and *Delete*.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] The acronym CRUD refers to the major operations which are implemented by databases.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] Each letter in the acronym can be mapped to a standard Structured Query Language (SQL) statement.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] Although relational databases are a common persistence layer in software applications, numerous other persistence layers exist.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] CRUD functionality can for example be implemented with document databases, object databases, XML databases, text files, or binary files.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] Some big data systems do not implement UPDATE, but have only a timestamped INSERT (journaling), storing a completely new version of the object each time.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] The acronym CRUD also appears in the discussion of RESTful APIs.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] In HTTP, the POST (create), GET (read), PUT (update), PATCH (partial update), and DELETE methods correspond to CRUD operations as they have storage management semantics, meaning that they let user agents directly manipulate the states of target resources.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] However, POST is not limited to resource creation and may also be used for process-oriented operations whose semantics exceed the scope of CRUD.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] CRUD is also relevant at the user interface level of most applications.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] For example, in address book software, the basic storage unit is an individual *contact entry*.
[src:loopback-node/create-read-update-and-delete] Because these operations are so fundamental, they are often documented and described under one comprehensive heading such as "contact management" or "document management" in general.
[src:loopback-node/doc-lb4] LoopBack is an award-winning, highly extensible, open-source Node.js and TypeScript framework based on Express.
[src:loopback-node/doc-lb4] It enables you to quickly create APIs and microservices composed from backend systems such as databases and SOAP or REST services.
[src:loopback-node/doc-lb4] The diagram below demonstrates how LoopBack serves as a composition bridge between incoming requests and outgoing integrations.
[src:loopback-node/doc-lb4] It also shows the different personas who are interested in various capabilities provided by LoopBack.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:loopback-node/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] The **OpenAPI Specification** (**OAS**), previously known as the **Swagger Specification**, is a specification for a machine-readable interface definition language for describing, producing, consuming and visualizing web services.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Originally developed to support the Swagger framework, it became a separate project in 2015, overseen by the OpenAPI Initiative, an open-source collaboration project of the Linux Foundation.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] An OpenAPI Description (OAD) represents a formal description of an API that tools can use to generate code, documentation, test cases, and more.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Swagger development began in early 2010 by Tony Tam, who was working at online dictionary company Wordnik.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] In March 2015, SmartBear Software acquired the open-source Swagger API specification from Reverb Technologies, Wordnik's parent company.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] In November 2015, SmartBear announced that it was donating the Swagger specification to a new organization called the OpenAPI Initiative, under the sponsorship of the Linux Foundation.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Other founding member companies included 3scale, Apigee, Capital One, Google, IBM, Intuit, Microsoft, PayPal, and Restlet.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] On 1 January 2016, the Swagger specification was renamed the OpenAPI Specification (OAS) and was moved to a new GitHub repository.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Two somewhat similar technologies, MuleSoft's RESTful API Modeling Language (RAML) and Apiary's API Blueprint, had been developed around the same time as what was then still called the Swagger Specification.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] The producers of both formats later joined the OpenAPI Initiative: Apiary in 2016 and MuleSoft in 2017.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] In July 2017, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.0.0 of its specification.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] In February 2021, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.1.0.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] In September 2025, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.2.0 of the OAS.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Notable features include structured tags, first-class streaming media type support, support for arbitrary HTTP methods, clearer example semantics for serializations, OAuth2 device flow and metadata enhancements, and clarified path templating and routing semantics.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] The OAS describes the format for OpenAPI Descriptions (OADs), which can be used by a variety of applications, libraries, and tools.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Applications can use OADs to automatically generate documentation of methods, parameters and data models.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] This helps keep the documentation, client libraries and source code in sync.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] When an OAD is used to generate source code stubs for servers, the process is called scaffolding.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] The paradigm of agreeing on an API contract first and then programming business logic afterwards, in contrast to coding the program first and then writing a retrospective description of its behavior as the contract, is called contract-first development.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Since the interface is determined before any code is written, downstream developers can mock the server behavior and start testing right away.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] In this sense, contract-first development is also a practice of shift-left testing.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Specification is language-agnostic.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] With OpenAPI's declarative resource specification, clients can understand and consume services without knowledge of server implementation or access to the server code.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Initiative sponsored APIStrat from 2017 to 2019, converting it into the API Specifications Confererence (ASC) from 2020 to 2022.
[src:loopback-node/openapi-specification] Starting in 2023, the initiative has instead sponsored OpenAPI tracks at multiple conferences throughout the year.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:loopback-node/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:loopback-node/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:loopback-node/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
